issue.title: Platform: Add SimpleTextInputExCompatDxe for EFI 1.1 compatibility
issue.body:
This driver provides SimpleTextInputEx protocol support for EFI 1.1 systems that lack native support for this protocol. Specifically designed to enable OpenShell text editor functionality on older UEFI implementations.

Key features:
- EFI 1.1 compatibility layer for SimpleTextInputEx protocol
- Function key support (F1-F11) for OpenShell
- Control character detection and mapping (Ctrl+A through Ctrl+Z)
- Non-intrusive operation with existing text input protocols
- Closes https://github.com/acidanthera/bugtracker/issues/1080

comment.body:
I think going with both is a good idea indeed. I think the right approach to do it should be as follows:

* Create a library (OpenCorePkg/Library/OcTextInputLib) with multiple .inf files with .c code implementing functions necessary to install the SimpleInputEx protocol.
    * OpenCorePkg/Library/OcTextInputLib/OcTextInputLib.inf could offer "normal" variant for use by the drivers.
    * OpenCorePkg/Library/OcTextInputLib/OcTextInputLocalLib.inf could offer "local" variant for use by OpenShell, and will use `OcRegisterBootServicesProtocol` instead of `gBS` within a constructor to install the service.
* In OpenCore we add `OcTextInputLib.inf` dependency and wire things through the configuration.
* In OpenShell we add `OcTextInputLocalLib.inf` dependency and use constructor-based approach to add a protocol.
* Separately we may create an additional driver inside `OpenCorePkg` (or perhaps even some other repository) using `OcTextInputLib.inf`, which can be used to offer compatibility outside of OpenCorePkg (e.g. for firmware injection).

This way we will not need hacks inside `audk`. Let me know if you need help, I guess I could take over after a certain point to perform the integration as I know the project codebase a little better.

issue.title: The JavaScript command doesn't execute in the Pre- or Post-HTML fields of blocks.

labels.name: Topic: Lava
labels.description: Related to the Lava templating language.

labels.name: Topic: CMS
labels.description: Related to data and components primarily for the external website.

issue.body:
### Description

The JavaScript command doesn't execute when added to the Pre- or Post-HTML fields of Obsidian blocks.

### Actual Behavior

Nothing runs. Changing out to inline <script> tags lets the script run.

### Expected Behavior

Ideally, the Pre- and Post-HTML fields should inject the js into the header like it's designed to do. If the Obsidian/Vue stack makes that difficult, it should be documented in the Lava guide and on the fields themselves, but that might not be best since I imagine it's breaking someone's code out there somewhere, and limits the benefits of the command.

### Steps to Reproduce

- Edit an Obsidian block
- Add this to the Pre-HTML:
```
{% javascript %}
    alert("Hello world?");
{% endjavascript %}
```

### Issue Confirmation

- [x] Perform a search on the [Github Issues](https://github.com/issues?q=is%3Aissue+user%3ASparkDevNetwork+-repo%3ARock) to see if your bug or enhancement is already reported.
- [x] Reproduced the problem on a fresh install or on the [demo site](https://rock.rocksolidchurchdemo.com/).

### Rock Version

17.1

### Client Culture Setting

en-US

@@ -0,0 +1,345 @@
+"""
+    Kaczmarz <: Solver
+
+An implementation of a Kaczmarz solver. Specifically, it is a solver that iteratively
+    updates a solution by projecting the solution onto a subspace of the row space of the 
+    linear system.
+
+# Mathematical Description
+Let ``A`` be an ``m \\times n`` matrix and consider the consistent linear system ``Ax=b``. 
+    We can view the solution to this linear system as lying at the intersection of the 
+    row hyperplanes, 
+    ``\\cap_{i \\in \\{1, \\ldots, m\\}}\\{u \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n} : A_{i \\cdot} u = b_i
+    \\}``,
+    where ``A_{i \\cdot}`` represents the ``i^\\text{th}`` row of ``A``. One way to find 
+    this interesection is to iteratively project some abritrary point, ``x`` from one 
+    hyperplane to the next, through 
+    ``
+    x_{+} = x + \\alpha \\frac{b_i - \\lange A_{i\\cdot}, x\\rangle}{\\| A_{i\\cdot}.
+    ``
+    Doing this with random permutation of ``i`` can lead to a geometric convergence 
+    [strohmer2009randomized](@cite).
+    Here ``\\alpha`` is viewed as an over-relaxation parameter and can improve convergence. 
+    One can also generalize this procedure to blocks by considering the ``S`` being a 
+    ``s \\times n`` random matrix. If we let ``\\tilde A = S A`` and ``\\tilde b = Sb`` 
+    then we can perform block kaczmarz as described by [needell2014paved](@cite) with 
+    ``
+    x_{+} = x + \\alpha \\tilde A^\\top (\\tilde A \\tilde A^\\top)^\\dagger 
+    (\\tilde b - \\tilde A x).
+    ``
+# Fields
+- `alpha::Float64`, the over-relaxation parameter. It is multiplied by the update and can 
+    affect convergence.
+- `compressor::Compressor`, a technique for forming the compressed rowspace of the linear 
+    system.
+- `log::Logger`, a technique for logging the progress of the solver.
+- `error::SolverError`, a method for estimating the progress of the solver.

issue.title: qemu_storage: Add compatibility for QEMU 10.1.0+ command help changes
issue.body:
QEMU 10.1.0+ changed the command help system where global "qemu-img -h"
no longer shows all command-specific options. Individual commands now
require "qemu-img COMMAND -h" to get their specific help text.

This change addresses compatibility issues by:

* Adding version detection for QEMU < 10.1.0 vs >= 10.1.0
* Implementing adaptive help text retrieval based on QEMU version
* Replacing static force-share capability detection with dynamic
  per-command capability checking
* Updating all force-share usage sites to use the new detection method
* Updating command support detection to work with both versions

The force-share capability (-U/--force-share) detection now works by:
- Legacy QEMU (< 10.1.0): Search for [-U] in global help text
- Modern QEMU (>= 10.1.0): Check command-specific help for --force-share

References:
- QEMU commit: https://gitlab.com/qemu-project/qemu/-/commit/bf5647ae24f3a539eb40003f3d3db95b9484b978

ID: 4179


<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->
## Summary by CodeRabbit

* **New Features**
  * Per-instance QEMU version detection for smarter compatibility.
  * Version-aware command help parsing and per-command capability checks.
  * Per-command detection of force-share support for snapshot, info, compare, and check operations.
  * Improved handling of backing-chain option across legacy and modern QEMU.

* **Bug Fixes**
  * Prevents errors when force-share/backing-chain options are unavailable on certain QEMU versions.
  * Ensures correct flags and behavior across legacy and modern QEMU, improving reliability of image operations.

pull_request.title: feat: Include password in user creation and update return values
pull_request.body:
This pull request updates the user creation and update logic in the Postgres repository to ensure the `password` field is included in both the returned columns and the scanned struct after an insert or update operation. This change helps maintain consistency and ensures the full user model, including the password, is available after these operations.

**Repository query and model updates:**

* Added the `password` field to the list of returned columns in both the `Create` and `Update` user queries in `repository.go`, ensuring the password is populated in the resulting `User` model. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL53-R59) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL262-R269)
* Updated the `Scan` calls to include the `Password` field, so the `User` struct returned from these methods contains the password value. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL53-R59) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL262-R269)

pull_request.title: test: Add concurrent fixture teardown test for Hypothesis
pull_request.body:
This PR improves test coverage for the Hypothesis integration by adding a new test case for concurrent fixture teardowns.

The new `test_hypothesis_concurrent_fixture_teardown` test validates that `async` fixtures with teardown logic behave correctly when run alongside other concurrent tasks. This helps ensure the robustness of `pytest-asyncio`'s fixture management in complex, real-world scenarios.

To accommodate Hypothesis's health checks for function-scoped fixtures, the test is decorated with `@settings(suppress_health_check=[HealthCheck.function_scoped_fixture])`.
